 Build IR Toolkit with GRR, Velociraptor & KAPE
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Install and configure GRR (Google Rapid Response) for remote forensic analysis
Set up Velociraptor for endpoint monitoring and incident response
Deploy KAPE (Kroll Artifact Parser and Extractor) for forensic artifact collection
Execute collection jobs to test each tool's functionality
Build a comprehensive incident response toolkit on a single Linux machine
Prerequisites
Basic Linux command-line knowledge
Understanding of incident response concepts
Familiarity with network configurations
Root/sudo access on the Linux machine
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides a Linux-based cloud machine for this lab. Simply click Start Lab to access your dedicated environment. The machine comes as bare metal with no pre-installed tools, requiring you to install all necessary components during the lab.

Task 1: Install and Configure GRR
Subtask 1.1: Install GRR Dependencies
# Update system packages
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

# Install required dependencies
sudo apt install -y python3 python3-pip python3-dev python3-venv
sudo apt install -y mysql-server mysql-client libmysqlclient-dev
sudo apt install -y build-essential libssl-dev libffi-dev
Subtask 1.2: Set Up MySQL Database
# Start MySQL service
sudo systemctl start mysql
sudo systemctl enable mysql

# Configure MySQL for GRR
sudo mysql -e "CREATE DATABASE grr;"
sudo mysql -e "CREATE USER 'grr'@'localhost' IDENTIFIED BY 'grrpassword';"
sudo mysql -e "GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON grr.* TO 'grr'@'localhost';"
sudo mysql -e "FLUSH PRIVILEGES;"
Subtask 1.3: Install GRR Server
# Create GRR directory
sudo mkdir -p /opt/grr
cd /opt/grr

# Create virtual environment
sudo python3 -m venv grr-env
sudo chown -R $USER:$USER /opt/grr

# Activate environment and install GRR
source grr-env/bin/activate
pip install --upgrade pip
pip install grr-response-server grr-response-client
Subtask 1.4: Configure GRR Server
# Initialize GRR configuration
grr_config_updater initialize

# Set database configuration
grr_config_updater set_var --var=Mysql.host --val=localhost
grr_config_updater set_var --var=Mysql.port --val=3306
grr_config_updater set_var --var=Mysql.database_name --val=grr
grr_config_updater set_var --var=Mysql.database_username --val=grr
grr_config_updater set_var --var=Mysql.database_password --val=grrpassword
Subtask 1.5: Start GRR Services
# Start GRR server components
grr_server --component admin_ui &
grr_server --component frontend &
grr_server --component worker &

# Verify GRR is running
ps aux | grep grr_server
Task 2: Install and Configure Velociraptor
Subtask 2.1: Download Velociraptor
# Create Velociraptor directory
mkdir -p /opt/velociraptor
cd /opt/velociraptor

# Download latest Velociraptor binary
wget https://github.com/Velocidex/velociraptor/releases/latest/download/velociraptor-linux-amd64
chmod +x velociraptor-linux-amd64
sudo ln -s /opt/velociraptor/velociraptor-linux-amd64 /usr/local/bin/velociraptor
Subtask 2.2: Generate Velociraptor Configuration
# Generate server configuration
velociraptor config generate > server.config.yaml

# Generate client configuration
velociraptor --config server.config.yaml config client > client.config.yaml
Subtask 2.3: Start Velociraptor Server
# Create data directory
mkdir -p /opt/velociraptor/data

# Start Velociraptor server
velociraptor --config server.config.yaml frontend -v &

# Start Velociraptor GUI
velociraptor --config server.config.yaml gui &
Subtask 2.4: Create Admin User
# Create admin user for web interface
velociraptor --config server.config.yaml user add admin --role administrator
Task 3: Install and Configure KAPE
Subtask 3.1: Install Wine for KAPE
# Install Wine to run KAPE on Linux
sudo apt install -y wine winetricks

# Configure Wine
winecfg
Subtask 3.2: Download and Set Up KAPE
# Create KAPE directory
mkdir -p /opt/kape
cd /opt/kape

# Download KAPE (Note: Requires registration on KrollCyber website)
# For this lab, we'll use a placeholder command
# wget https://www.kroll.com/kape/kape.zip
# unzip kape.zip

# Alternative: Use Eric Zimmerman's tools
wget https://download.mikestammer.com/net6/kape.zip
unzip kape.zip
Subtask 3.3: Configure KAPE Environment
# Set up KAPE configuration
cd /opt/kape
wine kape.exe --help

# Create output directory
mkdir -p /opt/kape/output
Task 4: Test Tool Functionality
Subtask 4.1: Test GRR Collection
# Access GRR web interface
echo "GRR Admin UI available at: http://localhost:8000"
echo "Default credentials: admin/admin"

# Test GRR client connection
cd /opt/grr
source grr-env/bin/activate
grr_client --config=/etc/grr/grr-client.yaml
Subtask 4.2: Test Velociraptor Collection
# Test Velociraptor client
velociraptor --config client.config.yaml client -v

# Run a simple artifact collection
velociraptor --config server.config.yaml artifacts collect Linux.Sys.Users --output_directory /tmp/velociraptor_output
Subtask 4.3: Test KAPE Collection
# Run KAPE collection test
cd /opt/kape
wine kape.exe --tsource /var/log --tdest /opt/kape/output --target LinuxLogs

# Verify output
ls -la /opt/kape/output/
Task 5: Verify Installation and Configuration
Subtask 5.1: Check Service Status
# Check all running processes
ps aux | grep -E "(grr|velociraptor|kape)"

# Check network ports
netstat -tlnp | grep -E "(8000|8080|8889)"
Subtask 5.2: Test Web Interfaces
# Display access information
echo "=== IR Toolkit Access Information ==="
echo "GRR Admin UI: http://localhost:8000"
echo "Velociraptor GUI: http://localhost:8889"
echo "Default GRR credentials: admin/admin"
echo "Velociraptor admin user created during setup"
Subtask 5.3: Create Test Collection Script
# Create automated collection script
cat > /opt/ir_collect.sh << 'EOF'
#!/bin/bash
echo "Starting IR Collection..."

# Create output directory with timestamp
OUTPUT_DIR="/opt/ir_output/$(date +%Y%m%d_%H%M%S)"
mkdir -p $OUTPUT_DIR

# Collect system information
echo "Collecting system info..."
uname -a > $OUTPUT_DIR/system_info.txt
ps aux > $OUTPUT_DIR/processes.txt
netstat -tlnp > $OUTPUT_DIR/network.txt

# Run Velociraptor collection
echo "Running Velociraptor collection..."
velociraptor --config /opt/velociraptor/server.config.yaml artifacts collect Linux.Sys.Users --output_directory $OUTPUT_DIR/velociraptor

echo "Collection completed: $OUTPUT_DIR"
EOF

chmod +x /opt/ir_collect.sh
Verification Commands
# Verify all tools are installed
which grr_server
which velociraptor
ls /opt/kape/

# Test collection script
/opt/ir_collect.sh

# Check output
ls -la /opt/ir_output/
Troubleshooting
GRR Issues:

If MySQL connection fails, verify database credentials
Check firewall settings for port 8000
Velociraptor Issues:

Ensure configuration files have correct permissions
Verify port 8889 is available
KAPE Issues:

Wine configuration may need adjustment for Windows executables
Check file permissions in output directory
Conclusion
You have successfully built a comprehensive incident response toolkit featuring three powerful open-source tools. GRR provides remote forensic capabilities, Velociraptor offers real-time endpoint monitoring, and KAPE enables efficient artifact collection. This toolkit forms the foundation for professional incident response operations, allowing you to collect, analyze, and respond to security incidents effectively. The skills gained in this lab are directly applicable to cybersecurity roles requiring hands-on incident response capabilities.
